                <li>
                  <b>Burners: </b>
                  <p>
                    Burners are the primary heating elements on a stove,
                    providing the necessary heat for cooking. In gas stoves,
                    burners release a controlled flame fueled by gas, while in
                    electric stoves, they consist of coils or smooth surfaces
                    that heat up when electricity passes through them. Common
                    issues with burners include clogging, misalignment, and wear
                    and tear. Gas burners can become clogged with food debris or
                    grease, which restricts gas flow and leads to uneven heating
                    or no ignition. Electric burners, on the other hand, might
                    develop hot spots or stop heating altogether due to damaged
                    coils. Regular cleaning and maintenance can prevent many of
                    these issues, but persistent problems may require component
                    replacement or professional repair.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <b>Ignition System: </b>
                  <p>
                    The ignition system is crucial in gas stoves as it generates
                    the spark needed to ignite the gas. This system typically
                    includes an electrode and a spark module. When the stove’s
                    control knob is turned, the spark module sends an electrical
                    current to the electrode, creating a spark that ignites the
                    gas. Common issues with the ignition system include
                    electrode misalignment, dirt buildup, or a malfunctioning
                    spark module. These problems can result in the burner
                    failing to ignite or producing a weak flame. Cleaning the
                    electrode and ensuring it is properly aligned can often
                    resolve these issues. If the spark module is faulty, it may
                    need to be replaced.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <b>Heating Elements:</b>
                  <p>
                    In electric stoves, heating elements are the components that
                    generate heat for cooking. They can be either coil elements
                    or smooth, flat elements in ceramic or glass top stoves. The
                    heating elements work by converting electrical energy into
                    heat. Over time, these elements can wear out or become
                    damaged, leading to uneven heating or complete failure to
                    heat. Visible signs of damage, such as cracks or burnt
                    spots, indicate the need for replacement. Additionally,
                    issues with the stove’s wiring or control board can affect
                    the performance of the heating elements, necessitating
                    professional inspection and repair.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <b>Thermostat:</b>
                  <p>
                    The thermostat in a stove regulates the oven's temperature,
                    ensuring that it maintains the set level for consistent
                    cooking results. It measures the internal temperature and
                    signals the heating element or burner to turn on or off as
                    needed. A malfunctioning thermostat can lead to inaccurate
                    temperature readings, causing the oven to overheat or
                    underheat. Symptoms of a faulty thermostat include unevenly
                    cooked food or an oven that doesn’t reach the desired
                    temperature. Calibrating or replacing the thermostat can
                    resolve these issues. Regularly checking the thermostat’s
                    accuracy with an oven thermometer can help detect problems
                    early.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <b>Control Panel: </b>
                  <p>
                    The control panel is the interface through which users
                    operate the stove, adjusting settings such as temperature,
                    timer, and cooking modes. It houses buttons, knobs, and
                    sometimes digital displays. Issues with the control panel
                    can range from unresponsive buttons to erratic behavior in
                    the display. These problems can be caused by dirt and grime,
                    worn-out components, or faults in the stove’s electronic
                    circuitry. Cleaning the control panel and ensuring it’s free
                    from grease can improve functionality. For more complex
                    issues, such as a malfunctioning circuit board, professional
                    repair or replacement of the control panel may be necessary.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <b>Oven Light:</b>
                  <p>
                    The oven light allows users to monitor the cooking process
                    without opening the oven door, which helps maintain a
                    consistent temperature. It typically consists of a light
                    bulb and a protective cover. Common issues with the oven
                    light include a burnt-out bulb or a faulty light switch.
                    Replacing the bulb is a straightforward fix, but if the
                    light doesn’t work after bulb replacement, the problem might
                    lie with the switch or the wiring. Ensuring the light cover
                    is clean and intact can also help maintain proper visibility
                    inside the oven.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <b>Gas Valve and Regulator:</b>
                  <p>
                    In gas stoves, the gas valve and regulator control the flow
                    and pressure of gas to the burners and oven. The gas valve
                    opens and closes to allow gas flow, while the regulator
                    ensures the gas is at the correct pressure for safe and
                    efficient operation. Issues with these components can lead
                    to gas leaks, weak flames, or burners that won’t ignite. A
                    gas odor around the stove is a serious indication of a
                    potential leak, requiring immediate attention. Regular
                    inspection and maintenance are crucial for these components,
                    and any suspected faults should be addressed by a qualified
                    technician to ensure safety.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                By understanding the roles and potential issues of these key
                stove parts, users can better maintain their appliances and
                address problems promptly, ensuring efficient and safe
                operation.
              </p>
