                <div class="FAQ">
                  <div class="fa">
                    <h3>What should I do if my dryer is not heating?</h3>
                  </div>

                  <div class="fa_plus">︾</div>

                  <div class="fa_minus">︽</div>
                </div>

                <div class="questions">
                  <p>
                    If your dryer is not heating, here are some steps you can
                    take to diagnose and potentially fix the problem:
                  </p>
                  <ol>
                    <li>
                      <b>Check the Power Supply: </b>Ensure that your dryer is
                      properly plugged in. Sometimes, the issue can be as simple
                      as a loose plug. Also, check your home's circuit breaker
                      to see if it has tripped. This is a common issue that can
                      occur with many home appliances, including washers and
                      ovens.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <b>Inspect the Heating Element: </b>The heating element
                      can burn out over time. You might need to open the back
                      panel of the dryer to check if it’s functioning correctly.
                      If you’re not comfortable doing this yourself, of course,
                      consider calling a professional.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <b>Clean the Lint Filter and Vent: </b>A blocked lint
                      filter or vent can cause your dryer to overheat and shut
                      down the heating element. Make sure these are clear of
                      debris. This is a good practice not just for dryers but
                      for other machines like washers and even refrigerators,
                      which can have their own filters and vents.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <b>Test the Thermal Fuse: </b>The thermal fuse is a safety
                      device that stops the dryer from overheating. If it’s
                      blown, the dryer will not heat. You can use a multimeter
                      to test it for continuity. If it’s bad, you’ll need to
                      replace it.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <b>Inspect the Thermostat: </b>Dryers have several
                      thermostats that regulate the temperature. If one of them
                      is faulty, it could be the reason your dryer is not
                      heating. Similar to the thermal fuse, you can test these
                      with a multimeter.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <b>Check the Timer: </b>The timer can sometimes
                      malfunction, preventing the dryer from advancing to the
                      heating cycle. This is less common but worth checking if
                      all other components seem to be in working order.
                    </li>
                  </ol>

                  <p>
                    If after these steps your dryer is still not heating, it
                    might be time to call a technician. They can diagnose more
                    complex issues that might be affecting your appliance.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    Remember, safety first. If you're not sure about anything,
                    especially when dealing with electrical components, it's
                    better to consult a professional. Your average homeowner can
                    handle many simple fixes, but some repairs are best left to
                    those with the right tools and expertise.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    For more detailed guides and troubleshooting tips, you can
                    visit online resources. One good place to start is the
                    manufacturer's website, which often has http:// support
                    pages and manuals. If the issue occurs on a Sunday and you
                    can't reach customer service, many websites and forums
                    provide word-of-mouth advice that might help you out.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    If you need to replace parts, you might need to drive a
                    truck to a local appliance parts store, or you could order
                    the parts online. Make sure to have the model number handy,
                    which is usually found inside the door or on the back of the
                    machine.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    Finally, always ensure that any repairs or checks you
                    undertake are done with the appliance unplugged and the gas
                    supply (if applicable) closed. Safety should always be your
                    top priority at home.
                  </p>
                </div>

                <div class="FAQ">
                  <div class="fa">
                    <h3>Why is my dryer making a loud noise?</h3>
                  </div>

                  <div class="fa_plus">︾</div>

                  <div class="fa_minus">︽</div>
                </div>

                <div class="questions">
                  <p>
                    If your dryer is making a loud noise, it can be quite
                    concerning. Here are some common reasons why this could be
                    happening and what you can do about it:
                  </p>
                  <ol>
                    <li>
                      <b>Foreign Objects: </b>Sometimes, items can get caught in
                      the drum or the lint trap. Check for objects like coins,
                      buttons, or small toys that might have been left in
                      pockets and made their way into the dryer. Just like you
                      would check a washer for stray items before starting a
                      load, make sure to inspect the dryer as well.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <b>Worn Drum Rollers: </b>The drum rollers support the
                      drum as it rotates. Over time, these can wear out and
                      cause a loud rumbling noise. If you suspect this is the
                      issue, you might need to replace the rollers. This is a
                      bit more involved and could require opening up the
                      machine.
                    </li>
                    <li>
