                <div class="questions">
                  <p>
                    There are several maintenance tasks you can perform on your
                    dryer to keep it running smoothly and efficiently. Here are
                    some steps you can take using common Home tools and a little
                    bit of time:
                  </p>
                  <ol>
                    <li>
                      <b>Clean the Lint Filter: </b>After every load, make sure
                      to clean the lint filter. This not only helps your dryer
                      work more efficiently but also reduces the risk of fire.
                      Much like cleaning the filters in your refrigerator or
                      oven, this is a simple yet crucial step.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <b>Check and Clean the Venting System: </b>At least once a
                      year, check the venting system for any obstructions. A
                      clogged vent can cause your dryer to overheat and become
                      less efficient. Unplug the dryer and disconnect the vent
                      hose from the back, then use a vacuum or a vent brush to
                      remove any lint buildup. This task is akin to defrosting a
                      freezer; it’s essential for optimal performance.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <b>Inspect the Drum Seals: </b>The drum seals help to keep
                      clothes from getting caught in the drum. Over time, these
                      seals can wear out. Open the dryer door and inspect the
                      seals for any signs of wear or damage. If they look worn,
                      you might need to replace them. This is a bit more
                      involved but can often be done at home with a basic repair
                      kit.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <b>Clean the Inside of the Drum: </b>Wipe down the inside
                      of the drum with a damp cloth to remove any residue or
                      lint. This is similar to how you might clean the interior
                      of an oven. A clean drum helps to ensure that your clothes
                      remain clean and free of lint.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <b>Check the Balance: </b>Make sure the dryer is level. An
                      unbalanced machine can cause excessive noise and wear on
                      the components. Use a level to check, and adjust the feet
                      as necessary. This is much like ensuring your oven is
                      level for even cooking.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <b>Examine the Power Cord: </b>Inspect the power cord for
                      any signs of wear or damage. If the cord looks frayed or
                      damaged, it’s crucial to replace it. This is a safety
                      precaution similar to checking the cord on your oven or
                      other home appliances.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <b>Lubricate Moving Parts: </b>Some parts of the dryer,
                      like the drum support rollers, may benefit from occasional
                      lubrication. Use a high-temperature lubricant designed for
                      appliances to keep these parts moving smoothly. This is
                      similar to maintaining the moving parts in an oven.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <b>Test the Door Latch: </b>Make sure the door latch works
                      properly. If the latch is loose or doesn’t catch well, it
                      can cause the dryer to stop mid-cycle. You can usually
                      tighten or replace the latch yourself with a screwdriver.
                    </li>
